      "analysis": "The possessive pronoun 'my' in the poem's very first line immediately establishes the Duke's attitude of ownership towards the Duchess. She is not named, not individualised, not given her own identity — she is 'my last Duchess', a possession defined entirely by her relationship to him. The word 'my' recurs throughout the poem and functions as a linguistic marker of the Duke's controlling psychology: he does not see people as autonomous beings but as objects that belong to him. The word 'last' is equally significant, implying a sequence — she is one in a series, replaceable, like items in a collection. Combined with 'painted on the wall', the line reduces a living woman to a decorative object, a piece of art hung for display. Browning establishes from the outset that the Duke views his wife as property, and the possessive pronoun is the grammatical embodiment of that worldview. The determiner 'my' also extends to other possessions later in the poem — 'my gift of a nine-hundred-years-old name' — revealing that the Duke places his wife and his ancestral title in the same category of things he owns. For a GCSE response, this is a powerful opening point: the very first word the Duke uses to describe his wife is a possessive determiner, revealing that ownership is his primary mode of relating to other people."
