      "analysis": "This is one of the poem's most powerful examples of dramatic irony. The Duke intends to criticise his wife — he finds fault in her warm, generous nature, her readiness to take pleasure in simple things. However, the reader recognises that the qualities the Duke despises are, in fact, virtues: kindness, openness, gratitude, and joy. The Duke's complaint reveals far more about his own character than about the Duchess's failings. His inability to appreciate her warmth exposes his coldness, his jealousy, and his pathological need to be the sole source of her happiness. The parenthetical hesitation 'how shall I say?' is itself deeply ironic: the Duke pretends to search delicately for the right words, performing false modesty, when in reality he has rehearsed this speech carefully and knows exactly what he wants to say. This feigned difficulty in expressing himself is a manipulative tactic designed to make his monstrous complaints sound reasonable. Browning ensures that the reader sees through the Duke's performance even as the envoy within the poem may not, creating a devastating gap between what is said and what is understood. The dramatic irony intensifies as the poem progresses, culminating in the Duke's apparent unawareness that he is confessing to murder while negotiating his next marriage."
