      "analysis": "Enjambment — the running-on of a sentence across line breaks without punctuation — is one of Browning's most important structural techniques in this poem. The heroic couplets (AABB rhyme scheme) should create a sense of neat, orderly closure at the end of each pair of lines, but the persistent enjambment works against this, pulling sentences across the boundaries and burying the rhymes within the flow of natural speech. This tension between the couplet structure and the enjambment mirrors the Duke's psychology: he desires perfect order and control (the couplets) but cannot fully contain his thoughts and emotions (the enjambment). In this particular example, the line break after 'had' creates a momentary suspension — the reader does not yet know what the Duchess 'had' — before the next line reveals 'A heart'. This enjambment enacts the Duke's hesitation and his struggle to articulate his grievance. More broadly, the enjambment throughout the poem creates the illusion of spontaneous, conversational speech, which is essential to the dramatic monologue form: the Duke must sound as though he is speaking naturally, not reciting a rehearsed speech, even though Browning has carefully crafted every line. The technique also prevents the listener from finding natural stopping points, replicating the experience of being trapped in conversation with a powerful, dominating speaker who will not allow interruption."
