      "analysis": "The portrait of the Duchess and the curtain that covers it form the poem's central symbol. In life, the Duke could not control the Duchess — she smiled at everyone, she appreciated sunsets and cherries and the white mule equally with his 'gift of a nine-hundred-years-old name'. In death or removal, he has finally achieved total control: she is frozen in paint, permanently beautiful, permanently smiling, and permanently silent. The curtain is the physical mechanism of this control — only the Duke decides who may look at her, when, and for how long. The emphatic repetition of 'I' at the end of the line ('but I') underscores his exclusive authority over access to the Duchess's image. The portrait symbolises the Duke's ideal relationship: the Duchess as a beautiful object that exists solely for his pleasure, available when he wishes and hidden when he does not. The curtain also symbolises concealment and revelation — the Duke draws it back to show the envoy, just as he inadvertently draws back the curtain on his own criminality throughout the monologue. The parenthetical delivery of this information, enclosed almost as an aside, makes it even more disturbing: the Duke considers his absolute monopoly over the Duchess's image to be so natural that it barely warrants emphasis. Browning creates a layered symbol in which art, ownership, control, and the silencing of women are all interconnected."
