      "quote": "She had / A heart — how shall I say? — too soon made glad",
      "analysis": "The parenthetical hesitation 'how shall I say?' is one of the poem's most psychologically revealing moments. On the surface, it appears to show the Duke searching for the right words, as though he is being diplomatic or tactful. However, this apparent hesitation is itself a performance — the Duke has clearly thought about this at length and knows exactly what he wants to say. The pause functions as a rhetorical device, designed to make the envoy (and the reader) lean in and pay closer attention. The phrase 'too soon made glad' is the Duke's central complaint against the Duchess: she was too easily pleased, too generous with her smiles and gratitude. What any reasonable person would consider virtues — warmth, kindness, an appreciative nature — the Duke reframes as moral failings. The enjambment splitting 'She had / A heart' across two lines enacts the Duke's attempt to control even the rhythm of his speech, parcelling out information at his own pace. The word 'heart' is significant because it is one of the few moments where the Duke acknowledges the Duchess as a feeling human being rather than an object, yet he immediately qualifies and criticises that feeling. The dash before 'too soon' creates a caesura that snaps the line into a judgement, revealing the Duke's contempt beneath his veneer of measured consideration.",
