      "quote": "since none puts by / The curtain I have drawn for you, but I",
      "analysis": "The curtain over the portrait is one of the poem's most potent symbols, and this line makes its significance explicit. In life, the Duke could not control who saw the Duchess or who made her smile. In death — or after her removal — he has achieved total control: only he decides who may look at her image. The repeated first-person pronoun 'I' at the end of the line, separated by the line break, lands with emphatic force, asserting the Duke's absolute authority. The phrase 'I have drawn for you' frames the act of revealing the portrait as a privilege bestowed by the Duke, reinforcing his role as gatekeeper and master of access. The curtain functions as a physical manifestation of the Duke's controlling nature — it is a barrier he can raise and lower at will, regulating the gaze of others. This also has a metatheatrical quality: the Duke is literally curating a viewing experience, controlling what the envoy sees and when he sees it, just as he controls the narrative of his marriage. The curtain symbolises the Duke's ideal relationship: one in which the other person is silent, still, beautiful, and entirely subject to his will. It is the ultimate act of objectification — the Duchess has been reduced from a living woman to an artwork behind a curtain, accessible only at the Duke's pleasure.",
